  <h1>ShiftKey vs CareRev vs ShiftMed: Gig Nursing Apps Compared the Right Way</h1>
  <p class="meta">Updated July 2026 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <a href="index.html">More nurse career guides &rarr;</a></p>

<div class="warning">
<strong>Independent review note:</strong> This is an unsponsored comparison. Platform policies, markets served, employment classifications, and pay mechanics change frequently and vary by city and facility. Treat everything below as a framework for evaluating the apps, then verify the current terms inside each app and in its independent-contractor or employment agreement before you work a shift.</div>

<p>Gig nursing apps promise the same thing: open the app, pick up a shift at a nearby facility, get paid quickly, owe nobody a schedule. But the three biggest names are built on different employment architectures, and that difference &mdash; not the interface, not the hourly number on the shift card &mdash; is what actually determines your taxes, your legal exposure, your cancellation risk, and whether the flexibility is real. Here is the comparison that matters.</p>

<h2>The one question that sorts everything: 1099 or W-2?</h2>
<p><strong>ShiftKey</strong> operates on an independent-contractor model: you are a 1099 business of one, bidding on shifts posted by facilities (historically heavy in skilled nursing and long-term care). <strong>CareRev</strong> and <strong>ShiftMed</strong> have generally positioned themselves closer to the W-2 side of the spectrum for many roles and markets, with CareRev known for acute-care hospital placements and ShiftMed spanning post-acute and acute settings &mdash; but classification can differ by market, role, and over time, so confirm your own classification in writing before your first shift.</p>
<p>Why this dominates everything else:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Taxes.</strong> A 1099 platform withholds nothing. You owe income tax plus self-employment tax, paid quarterly, yourself. Nurses who treat 1099 gig pay like W-2 pay meet a brutal April surprise &mdash; the mechanics are in our <a href="quarterly-estimated-taxes-1099-nurses-2026.html">quarterly estimated taxes guide for 1099 nurses</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Malpractice and injury.</strong> W-2 employees typically get workers' compensation coverage and some employer liability umbrella. A 1099 contractor may have neither. If you work 1099 shifts, an individual malpractice policy stops being optional &mdash; see the <a href="rn-malpractice-insurance-guide-2026.html">RN malpractice insurance guide</a> &mdash; and ask specifically what happens if you're injured on shift.</li>
<li><strong>Rate math.</strong> A 1099 hourly rate is not comparable to a W-2 hourly rate. After self-employment tax and zero benefits, a 1099 rate needs to be meaningfully higher than a W-2 rate just to break even. Comparing shift cards across apps without adjusting for classification is the most common mistake gig nurses make.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How each model actually feels to work</h2>
<h3>ShiftKey: the auction</h3>
<p>ShiftKey's signature mechanic is bidding &mdash; you propose your rate for a posted shift and the facility accepts or passes. That cuts both ways. In undersupplied markets and hard-to-fill shifts (nights, weekends, holidays), bidding lets you name a premium. In saturated markets, nurses underbid each other and the clearing rate sinks. The skill is treating your bid like a business decision: know your personal floor (your fully-loaded W-2 equivalent plus a margin for taxes, insurance, and no benefits) and never bid below it just to win a shift.</p>
<h3>CareRev: the hospital-adjacent per diem pool</h3>
<p>CareRev built its reputation on acute-care facilities &mdash; a meaningful distinction for ICU, ED, and med-surg nurses who want gig flexibility without leaving the hospital environment that keeps their skills sharp and their resume credible for <a href="crna-school-interview-questions-2026.html">CRNA applications</a> or future staff roles. Expect credentialing that looks more like a hospital onboarding: competency checklists, unit orientation expectations, and attendance standards closer to employment than to gig work.</p>
<h3>ShiftMed: the volume network</h3>
<p>ShiftMed's pitch is breadth &mdash; a large facility network across post-acute and acute care, W-2-style features in many markets (some offer instant or same-day pay and guaranteed-shift mechanics), and heavy shift volume. For nurses in mid-size markets where the other platforms are thin, ShiftMed is often simply the app with shifts available. As always, the fine print on cancellation windows and attendance scoring matters more than the marketing.</p>

