<h2>The tradeoffs nobody puts on the shift card</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>No guaranteed hours.</strong> Gig shift supply is cyclical. When hospital budgets tighten or a market saturates with nurses, the board empties. Gig income should be a supplement or a deliberately-chosen season, not a mortgage plan &mdash; the same logic as our <a href="weekend-option-vs-per-diem-vs-travel-nurse-2026.html">per diem vs travel comparison</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Deactivation risk.</strong> Every platform scores reliability. Late cancellations and no-shows can throttle your visibility or deactivate your account, often algorithmically and with limited appeal. Read the cancellation window rules like a contract clause &mdash; because they are one.</li>
<li><strong>Orientation reality.</strong> You will walk into unfamiliar units with minimal orientation. Charting system access, med room codes, and where the crash cart lives are your first fifteen minutes. Experienced nurses thrive; new grads generally should not start here.</li>
<li><strong>The first-shift credential scramble.</strong> Licenses, BLS/ACLS, immunization records, TB, fit testing, background check &mdash; each platform wants its own uploads. Keep one master digital folder; it turns a two-week onboarding into two days.</li>
</ul>

<h2>A sane strategy for using them</h2>
<p>The strongest position is a hybrid: keep a PRN or part-time W-2 anchor (benefits, retirement access, acute-care skill maintenance) and layer gig shifts on top at rates above your floor. Onboard with two platforms, not one &mdash; supply differs by week, and cross-checking shift cards keeps each app honest. If you go 1099-heavy, run it like the business it legally is: separate bank account, mileage log, quarterly tax payments, and your own malpractice policy from day one.</p>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Bottom line:</strong> Pick by employment model first, market coverage second, and interface last. ShiftKey rewards nurses who can price themselves; CareRev suits hospital nurses who want acute-care gig shifts; ShiftMed often wins on sheer availability. Whatever you choose, know your rate floor, protect your reliability score, and never work a 1099 shift without a tax plan and your own malpractice coverage.</div>

